%text A function $f(x)$ defined in $[a,b]$ is % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{cNN}
\hline & \text{If} & \text{Remember} \\ \hline \text{Increasing} & f'(x) \geq 0 & f'(x)\text{ can be } 0 \\ \hline \text{Strictly increasing} & f'(x) > 0 & f'(x)\neq 0 \\ \hline \text{Decreasing} & f'(x) \leq 0 & f'(x)\text{ can be } 0 \\ \hline \text{Strictly decreasing} & f'(x) < 0 & f'(x)\neq 0 \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text \textbf{Maxima \& Minima} The point at which $f(x)$ stops rising and start falling is called a \underline\text{maxima} Similarly, the point at which $f(x)$ stops falling and starts rising is called a \underline\text{minima} Maxima \& minima are both \underline\text{extrema } points The conditions for classifying an extrema as a maxima or a minima are given below % \begin{align} \begin{tabular}{cNN}
\hline & f'(x) & f''(x) \\ \hline Maxima & 0 & < 0 \\ \hline Minima & 0 & > 0 \\ \hline \end{tabular} \end{align} %text \textbf{Remember:} $f'(x) = 0$ at all extrema points. But one must look at $f''(x)$ to know whether the extrema is a \underline\text{maxima or a minima }%
